\page org_mitk_views_docker_spatialkmeans Spatial K-Means View

\imageMacro{SpatialKMeansIcon.svg,"Icon of the Spatial K-Means View",2.00}

\tableofcontents

\section org_mitk_views_docker_spatialkmeans_intro Introduction

The Spatial K-Means View provides a Docker-based spatial clustering analysis tool for mass spectrometry imaging data. This plugin uses spatially-constrained k-means clustering to identify spatial patterns in MSI data while taking into account the spatial arrangement of pixels.

\section org_mitk_views_docker_spatialkmeans_prereqs Prerequisites

- Docker must be installed and running on your system
- The Docker image ghcr.io/cemos-mannheim/spatialkmeansdocker:latest will be automatically pulled when needed
- A spectrum image must be loaded in M2aia

\section org_mitk_views_docker_spatialkmeans_usage Usage

1. Select a spectrum image from the Data Manager
2. Set the number of clusters (k) - default is 5
3. Set the smoothing radius (r) for spatial constraint - default is 1.0
4. Click "Run Spatial K-Means Clustering"

The plugin will:
- Extract the current ion image from the selected spectrum
- Run the spatial k-means clustering algorithm in a Docker container
- Create a multi-label segmentation showing the identified clusters
- Automatically assign distinct colors to each cluster

\section org_mitk_views_docker_spatialkmeans_params Parameters

- **Number of Clusters (k)**: The number of clusters to identify (2-100, default: 5)
- **Smoothing Radius (r)**: Spatial smoothing radius for the clustering constraint (0.1-100, default: 1.0). Higher values enforce stronger spatial coherence.

\section org_mitk_views_docker_spatialkmeans_output Output

The result is a multi-label segmentation image where each label represents a spatially coherent cluster. Clusters are automatically colored and can be visualized and edited using standard M2aia segmentation tools.

*/
